                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="15226399" author="garydgregory" created="Tue, 5 Apr 2016 14:51:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Sounds reasonable. Thoughts from others?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15226461" author="ralph.goers@dslextreme.com" created="Tue, 5 Apr 2016 15:28:54 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;To me, it sounds like another bug report waiting to happen.  If the current configuration file has a time of 2pm and the &quot;new&quot; one has a time of 1pm, why is the &quot;new&quot; one newer?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15226834" author="garydgregory" created="Tue, 5 Apr 2016 18:19:20 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I would guess that the reporter of this ticket would say &quot;because it is different&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What matters it seems is that the file is different, not it&apos;s &quot;age&quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If I have a couple complex configurations I want to toggle between. How do I do that. Myself, I comment in and out XML fragments ATM, that&apos;s quite a pain. Moving files around is easy in comparison. You might have some redundancy in the various files, but that&apos;s part of the trade-off.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15226881" author="ralph.goers@dslextreme.com" created="Tue, 5 Apr 2016 18:38:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yeah - I guess we are just trying to detect a change in the configuration, not that it is newer.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15226924" author="garydgregory" created="Tue, 5 Apr 2016 18:56:17 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ll run a local build with this change just to make sure nothing breaks.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15226951" author="garydgregory" created="Tue, 5 Apr 2016 19:17:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In Git master. Please verify and close.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
